{"id":"2112.09199","submitter":"Nathan Shettell","authors":"Nathan Shettell and Damian Markham","title":"Quantum Metrology with Delegated Tasks","comments":"13 page main text, 7 page appendix, 3 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 106, 052427 (2022)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.106.052427","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  A quantum metrology scheme can be decomposed into three quantum tasks: state\npreparation, parameter encoding and measurements. Consequently, it is\nimperative to have access to the technologies which can execute the\naforementioned tasks to fully implement a quantum metrology scheme. In the\nabsence of one or more of these technologies, one can proceed by delegating the\ntasks to a third party. However, doing so has security ramifications: the third\nparty can bias the result or leak information. In this article, we outline\ndifferent scenarios where one or more tasks are delegated to an untrusted (and\npossibly malicious) third party. In each scenario, we outline cryptographic\nprotocols which can be used to circumvent malicious activity. Further, we link\nthe effectiveness of the quantum metrology scheme to the soundness of the\ncryptographic protocols.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 16 Dec 2021 20:54:37 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 25 Nov 2022 03:03:50 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-11-28"}
