{"id":"2112.09369","submitter":"Akira Matsumura","authors":"Akira Matsumura","title":"Path-entangling evolution and quantum gravitational interaction","comments":"21 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 105, 042425 (2022)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.105.042425","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph gr-qc","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  We explore a general feature of the interaction mediated by the gravitational\nfields of spatially superposed masses. For this purpose, based on quantum\ninformation theory, we characterize the evolution of two particles each in a\nsuperposition state of paths. The evolution is assumed to be given by a\ncompletely positive trace-preserving (CPTP) map. We further assume that the\nprobability of particle being on each path is unchanged during the evolution.\nThis property is called population-preserving. We examine when a\npopulation-preserving CPTP map can create entanglement in terms of separable\noperations, which form a large class of local operations and classical\ncommunication (LOCC). In general, entanglement is not always generated by\ninseparable or non-LOCC operations, and one can consider a model of gravity\ndescribed by an inseparable operation which does not create entanglement.\nHowever, we find that a population-preserving CPTP map is inseparable if and\nonly if it can create entanglement. This means that the above model of gravity\nis incompatible with the possible evolution of spatially superposed masses.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 17 Dec 2021 07:57:35 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 10 Jan 2022 08:44:30 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 1 Apr 2022 09:56:38 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-04-19"}
